# Claude Reflect — Architecture

This document is the authoritative reference for how every piece of the app connects. Read it before writing or modifying any code. If a request from me contradicts this document, ask before acting.

## 1. System Overview

Claude Reflect is a single-page React application that wraps an AI chat interface with a real-time reasoning-transparency layer. When the user sends a query, the app makes two sequential Groq API calls — one for the main response and one for a structured JSON reflection that analyzes that response. Both render in a Claude-style interface: the main response in the central chat area, and the reflection (reasoning skeleton, uncertainty flags, gap disclosure, critical question gate) in a right-side Reflect panel. A third on-demand Groq call powers the "Help me think through this" follow-up inside the critical question gate. Chat history is held in React state for the session only — no database, no persistence beyond `localStorage` for theme and onboarding state.

## 2. Data Flow

```
[User types query in InputBar]
       │
       ▼
[ChatArea adds user message to messages[] for current chat]
       │
       ▼
[Frontend POST /api/chat  body: { type: "main", messages: [...current conversation] }]
       │
       ▼
[Vercel Serverless Function api/chat.js]
       │  routes on body.type → main
       │  calls Groq /openai/v1/chat/completions
       │  model: llama-3.3-70b-versatile, temperature: 0.7, max_tokens: 1500
       ▼
[Main response text returned to frontend as { response: "..." }]
       │
       ▼
[ChatArea appends assistant message; ThinkingIndicator hides]
       │
       ▼  (immediately, in parallel with paint of main response)
[Frontend POST /api/chat  body: { type: "reflection", query, response }]
       │
       ▼
[Vercel Serverless Function]
       │  routes on body.type → reflection
       │  calls Groq with strict JSON-only system prompt
       │  model: llama-3.3-70b-versatile, temperature: 0.3, max_tokens: 2000
       ▼
[Reflection raw text returned as { reflection: "..." }]
       │
       ▼
[parseReflection.js strips markdown fences, JSON.parse inside try/catch,
 validates shape, returns parsed object or null]
       │
       ▼
[ReflectPanel receives parsed object, renders four components:
   • ReasoningSkeleton (reasoning_skeleton[])
   • UncertaintyFlags  (uncertainty_flags[])
   • GapDisclosure     (gaps[])
   • CriticalQuestion  (critical_question)
 ]
       │
       ▼
[matchSentences.js walks sentence_labels[], finds each sentence in the
 rendered main response, attaches a ConfidenceIndicator dot to each match]
       │
       ▼
[Cross-link wiring: clicking a flagged sentence scrolls Reflect panel
 to its flag and pulses it; clicking a flag pulses the sentence]
       │
       ▼
[User reads. If they click "Help me think through this" on the critical question:
   Frontend POST /api/chat  body: { type: "followup", query, response,
                                    criticalQuestion, briefSummary }
   → routes on body.type → followup
   → calls Groq, model: llama-3.3-70b-versatile, temperature: 0.5, max_tokens: 800
   → response renders inline beneath the question]
```

**Why two calls, not one streaming call:** the reflection requires the *complete* main response as input. Streaming the main response while computing reflection in the same turn would require post-stream chaining anyway. Doing them as two sequential POSTs from the frontend keeps the serverless function stateless and makes failures isolatable — if reflection fails, the main response is unaffected.

**Why all three calls go through one `/api/chat` endpoint:** keeps Vercel serverless function count at one (free tier friendly), keeps API key handling in a single place, makes adding logging/rate-limiting trivial later.

